05842nam a22008655i 9781501752933DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020011026  a97815017529337 a10.1515/97815017529332doi  a(DE-B1597)548877  a(OCoLC)1145896482  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aPL747.57.M577bM58 2020 4aPL747.57.M577bM58 2021 7aHIS0210002bisacsh04a895.6091122231 aMitchell, Arthur M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDisruptions of Daily Life :bJapanese Literary Modernism in the World /cArthur M. Mitchell. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (276 p.) :b4 b&w halftones, 3 color halftones, 2 charts  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute, Columbia University00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Shattering the Status Quo: Reading Modernism in the Early Twentieth Century -- t1. Fetishism of the West in Tanizaki Jun’ichiro¯’s A Fool’s Love -- t2. Subversions of Ethnicity in Yokomitsu Riichi’s Neo-Sensationist Writings -- t3. Kawabata Yasunari’s The Scarlet Gang of Asakusa and the Narrative of the Present -- t4. “Love” and (Male) Subjectivity in Hirabayashi Taiko’s “In the Charity Ward” -- tCoda: Against the National Literary Narrative -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDisruptions of Daily Life explores the mass media landscape of early twentieth century in order to uncover the subversive societal impact of four major Japanese authors: Tanizaki Jun'ichirō, Yokomitsu Riichi, Kawabata Yasunari, and Hirabayashi Taiko. Arthur Mitchell examines this literature against global realities through a modernist lens, studying an alternative modernism that challenges the Western European model.Through broad surveys of discussions surrounding Japanese life in the 1920s, Mitchell locates and examines flourishing divergent ideologies of the early twentieth century such as gender, ethnicity, and nationalism. He unravels how the narrative and linguistic strategies of modernist texts interrogated the innocence of this language, disrupting their hold on people's imagined relationship to daily life. These modernist works often discursively displaced the authority of their own claims by inadvertently exposing the global epistemology of East vs. West. Mitchell's reading of these formalist texts expands modernism studies into a more translational dialogue by locating subversions within the local historical culture and allowing readers to make connections to the time and place in which the texts were written.In highlighting the unbreakable link between literature and society, Disruptions of Daily Life reaffirms the value of modernist fiction and its ability to make us aware of how realities are constructed—and how those realities can be changed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aJapanese literatureyShōwa period, 1926-1989xHistory and criticism. 0aJapanese literatureyShōwa period, 1926-1989xHistory and criticism. 0aJapanese literatureyTaishō period, 1912-1926xHistory and criticism. 0aJapanese literatureyTaishō period, 1912-1926xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzJapanxHistoryy20th century. 0aModernism (Literature)zJapan. 4aAsian Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aMedia Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Japan.2bisacsh  aTanizaki Jun’ichirō, Yokomitsu Riichi, Kawabata Yasunari, Hirabayashi Taiko.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070